\begin_body

\begin_layout Title
Algebra Exercises
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout


\backslash
begin{ex}
\backslash
label{ex}
\end_layout

\end_inset

 Let 
\begin_inset Formula $R$
\end_inset

 be a ring and suppose that for all units 
\begin_inset Formula $u$
\end_inset

 in 
\begin_inset Formula $R$
\end_inset

, either 
\begin_inset Formula $1+u=0$
\end_inset

 or 
\begin_inset Formula $1+u$
\end_inset

 is a unit.
 Show that 
\begin_inset Formula $R$
\end_inset

 is nilpotent-free and that 
\begin_inset Formula $R$
\end_inset

 contains a largest field 
\begin_inset Formula $K\subseteq R$
\end_inset

.
 Conversely, suppose 
\begin_inset Formula $R$
\end_inset

 is nilpotent-free and contains a largest field 
\begin_inset Formula $K\subseteq R$
\end_inset

.
 Show that for all units that for all units 
\begin_inset Formula $u$
\end_inset

 in 
\begin_inset Formula $R$
\end_inset

, either 
\begin_inset Formula $1+u=0$
\end_inset

 or 
\begin_inset Formula $1+u$
\end_inset

 is a unit.
 
\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout


\backslash
end{ex}
\end_layout

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout


\backslash
begin{sol}label{sol}
\end_layout

\end_inset

 We first assume that for all units 
\begin_inset Formula $u$
\end_inset

 in 
\begin_inset Formula $R$
\end_inset

, either 
\begin_inset Formula $1+u=0$
\end_inset

 or 
\begin_inset Formula $1+u$
\end_inset

 is a unit.
 We claim that 
\begin_inset Formula $R^{\times}\cup\{0\}$
\end_inset

 is a field (and in fact the largest field contained in 
\begin_inset Formula $R$
\end_inset

).
 Indeed, first note that it is closed under multiplication and addition:
 given 
\begin_inset Formula $u,v\in R^{\times}\cup\{0\}$
\end_inset

, we have
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
u+v=u(1+v/u)=\begin{cases}
0 & \text{if }u=-v\\
\text{nonzero unit} & \text{else}
\end{cases}
\]

\end_inset

Also it shares the same identity as 
\begin_inset Formula $R$
\end_inset

 (namely 
\begin_inset Formula $1$
\end_inset

).
 Thus 
\begin_inset Formula $R^{\times}\cup\{0\}$
\end_inset

 is a subring of 
\begin_inset Formula $R$
\end_inset

.
 Furthermore, every nonzero element in 
\begin_inset Formula $R^{\times}\cup\{0\}$
\end_inset

 is clearly invertible, thus 
\begin_inset Formula $R^{\times}\cup\{0\}$
\end_inset

 is a field.
 Let us denote this field 
\begin_inset Formula $K=R^{\times}\cup\{0\}$
\end_inset

.
 Thus 
\begin_inset Formula $R$
\end_inset

 is a 
\begin_inset Formula $K$
\end_inset

-algebra.
 In fact, 
\begin_inset Formula $K$
\end_inset

 is the largest field contained in 
\begin_inset Formula $R$
\end_inset

 (if 
\begin_inset Formula $K'$
\end_inset

 was another field contained in 
\begin_inset Formula $R$
\end_inset

, then 
\begin_inset Formula $K'\subseteq R^{\times}\subseteq K$
\end_inset

).
 Furthermore, note that 
\begin_inset Formula $R$
\end_inset

 doesn't contain any nilpotents since a niplotent plus a unit is a unit
 (if 
\begin_inset Formula $\varepsilon^{n}=0$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $uv=1$
\end_inset

, then 
\begin_inset Formula $(u+\varepsilon)\sum_{i=1}^{n-1}v^{i}\varepsilon^{i-1}=1$
\end_inset

).
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset space ~
\end_inset


\begin_inset space ~
\end_inset


\begin_inset space ~
\end_inset

Now we prove the converse.
 Suppose 
\begin_inset Formula $R$
\end_inset

 is nilpotent-free and that 
\begin_inset Formula $R$
\end_inset

 contains a largest field 
\begin_inset Formula $K\subseteq R$
\end_inset

.
 Let 
\begin_inset Formula $u$
\end_inset

 be a unit in 
\begin_inset Formula $R$
\end_inset

.
 Since 
\begin_inset Formula $R$
\end_inset

 is nilpotent-free, we have an inclusion of rings 
\begin_inset Formula $K\subseteq K(u)\subseteq R$
\end_inset

.
 Since 
\begin_inset Formula $K$
\end_inset

 is the largest field contained in 
\begin_inset Formula $R$
\end_inset

, we must have 
\begin_inset Formula $K=K(u)$
\end_inset

.
 It follows that 
\begin_inset Formula $u\in K$
\end_inset

, and hence either 
\begin_inset Formula $1+u=0$
\end_inset

 or 
\begin_inset Formula $1+u$
\end_inset

 is a unit.
 
\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout


\backslash
end{sol}
\end_layout

\end_inset


\end_layout

